  "prompt": "What are the causes for receding gums?",
  "response": "Receding gums, also known as gingival recession, can be caused by a variety of factors. Here are some common causes:\n\n1. **Periodontal Disease:** This is the most common cause of gum recession. Periodontal disease is an infection of the gums that can destroy the gum tissue and the supporting bone that holds your teeth in place. It leads to inflammation and recession over time.\n\n2. **Poor Oral Hygiene:** Insufficient brushing and flossing can lead to plaque buildup, which can cause gum disease and recession.\n\n3. **Genetics:** Some people are more prone to gum recession due to genetic factors. If you have a family history of gum disease, you may be at higher risk.\n\n4. **Aggressive Brushing:** Brushing your teeth too hard or using a hard-bristled toothbrush can damage the gums and lead to recession.\n\n5. **Tobacco Use:** Smoking or using other forms of tobacco can cause gum disease and contribute to gum recession.\n\n6. **Hormonal Changes:** Fluctuations in hormones, such as those experienced during pregnancy, menopause, or puberty, can make gums more susceptible to recession.\n\n7. **Misaligned Teeth or Bite:** Teeth that are not properly aligned can put extra pressure on the gums and bone, leading to recession.\n\n8. **Grinding and Clenching:** Bruxism, or the habit of grinding and clenching your teeth, can exert pressure on the gums and cause them to recede.\n\n9. **Poor Nutrition:** Lack of certain nutrients can affect the health of your gums, making them more susceptible to recession.\n\n10. **Medical Conditions:** Some medical conditions, such as diabetes, can increase the risk of gum disease and recession.\n\n11. **Lip or Tongue Piercings:** Jewelry can rub against the gums, causing irritation and recession over time.\n\nAddressing the underlying causes and maintaining good oral hygiene practices, such as regular dental check-ups and proper brushing and flossing techniques, can help prevent further gum recession. If you notice signs of receding gums, it\u2019s important to consult with a dental professional for appropriate diagnosis and treatment.",
